[[sn:akamiya Hachiman-sha (Ōita City)]]

'''Wakamiya Hachimangū''' (若宮八幡社) is a [[Shinto shrine|shrine]] located in Uenomachi, {{ill|Ōita City|ja|大分市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōita Prefecture|ja|大分県|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

The shrine is situated at the base of the Ueno Hills in the southern part of Ōita City, facing the Ōita Central Main Road (an urban planned road named Shōnohara-Sano Line) that opened in {{ill|2008|ja|平成20th year|12=draft}}. It borders the {{ill|Ōita Municipal Uenogaoka Junior High School|ja|大分市立上野ヶ丘中学校|12=draft}} to the west and the elevated tracks of the Kyūdai Main Line to the north.

== History ==

According to the shrine's tradition, it was established in {{ill|1196|ja|建久7th year|12=draft}} when {{ill|Ōtomo no Yasunao|ja|大友能直|12=draft}}, the first head of the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大友氏|12=draft}}, brought a divided spirit of {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|ja|鶴岡八幡宮|12=draft}} to the region while serving as the governor of the provinces of {{ill|Buzen Province|ja|豊前国|12=draft}} and {{ill|Bungo Province|ja|豊後国|12=draft}}. Initially located in Furukawazuru (present-day Iwata-chō), the shrine was moved to its current eastern site in {{ill|1201|ja|建仁元年|12=draft}} due to repeated flooding from the Ōita River. The shrine's location is depicted in the "Funaikozu," a map of Funai from the Tenshō period (circa {{ill|1581|ja|天正9th year|12=draft}} to {{ill|1586|ja|天正14th year|12=draft}}).<ref>{{文化遺産オンライン|95170|府内古図}}</ref>

Historically, the shrine was revered by the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大友氏|12=draft}}, who regarded it as a guardian of their castle in Funai. It was situated in the southwest ({{ill|Ura Kimon|ja|裏鬼門|12=draft}}, the "back demon gate") relative to the clan's residence. Successive clan heads, including {{ill|Ōtomo Sōrin|ja|大友宗麟|12=draft}}, funded its reconstruction and maintenance.<ref name="sumiyoshi">{{Cite report|和書
|url=https://www.city.oita.oita.jp/o169/documents/sumiyoshijinnjyanosaireikarashinnkyuufunaimatome.pdf
|title=Ōita City Historical Landscape Conservation Plan
|chapter=Chapter 2: Festivals in Old and New Funai
|page=108
|publisher=Ōita City
|date=2019-06
|accessdate=2020-01-13}}</ref>

During the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|12=draft}}, the shrine was moved to Minamishinchi (present-day Funaimachi 3-chome) in {{ill|1881|ja|明治14th year|12=draft}}. However, due to urbanization and space constraints, it was relocated back to its current site in {{ill|1921|ja|大正10th year|12=draft}}. The former site later became Wakadake Park and was eventually replaced by the Wakadake Building.<ref name="konjaku">{{Cite web|和書
|url=http://www.nan-nan.jp/lib/oita011a1.pdf
|title=Ōita Then and Now: Chapter 11 - Wakamatsu Street
|author=Katsumi Watanabe
|publisher=Ōita Godō Shimbunsha
|date=2007-10-26
|accessdate=2020-01-13}}</ref>

In {{ill|2003|ja|平成15th year|12=draft}}, part of the shrine's grounds was used for the construction of the Ōita Central Main Road. The shrine buildings were renovated and moved to the western section of the grounds.<ref name="sumiyoshi" /><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.oitatv.com/chiiki/index.php?id=1078 
|title=Passionate Local Spirit: Let's Visit Summer Festivals
|newspaper=Ōita Godō Shimbun
|date=2009-07-08}}</ref>

